         <abstract>
            <p>This study examines management proposals to increase the authorized shares of common stock and the resulting valuation consequences. For industrial firms the most common use of the additional shares is for stock dividends and splits. No revaluation effects are observed around the authorization proposals. Utilities are most likely to use newly approved shares for equity issues. Here the evidence, while mixed, suggests the market reaction to the authorization announcement is, on average, positive. Given previous research documenting negative price reactions to new equity issues, this result is surprising. A possible explanation for this reaction based on investment opportunities is offered.</p>
         </abstract>
